_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>BBSRC Responsive mode grant</gtr:description><gtr:end>2019-06-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>BB/N018656/1</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>B4D1F0A0-8552-47A6-82D3-6C854C1F87FD</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58c29ff612b7c9.72410070</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-06-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>415854</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>14-ERASynBio BioOrigami</gtr:description><gtr:end>2017-08-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>BB/M005739/1</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>82E7D832-53E2-4F7E-AD28-1332BAB22B7B</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5463ae7227bf97.58571303</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2014-09-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>30000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Single-molecule analysis of influenza virus transcription and replication</gtr:description><gtr:end>2019-03-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Medical Research Council (MRC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>MR/N010744/1</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>AB21D183-A6C3-455E-B48A-FC8AABEEDEDD</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58bd6357480e07.06743362</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-04-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>1587000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Wellcome Trust Investigator award</gtr:description><gtr:end>2021-02-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Wellcome Trust</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>110164/Z/15/Z</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>01C0A017-A4B7-46EE-8083-9AA977BD3736</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58c29f2be64440.91251839</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-02-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>5074190</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>SynbiCITE - an Imperial College led Innovation and Knowledge Centre (IKC) in Synthetic Biology</gtr:description><gtr:end>2018-09-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>EP/L011573/1</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>4C19666C-2300-4F02-BDB2-DC54783B7AAE</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5463ad01a51417.51634469</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2013-10-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>420000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Responsive mode</gtr:description><gtr:end>2019-03-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Medical Research Council (MRC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>MR/N010744/1</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>55002DD2-44E9-437C-8B83-D8C9D3FEB6BC</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58c2a084a53179.48128089</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-04-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>1170144</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Critical Mass Award</gtr:description><gtr:end>2020-10-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>EP/P000479/1</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>8DEBF614-EF3D-4CA0-A28B-523CB60BCCCD</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58c001bb2641f8.87679580</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-11-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>1) 'Click ligation' has a very broad range of possible applications, including the development of new methods for the discovery of new functional molecules. Techniques that we have developed for the creation of libraries of molecules, from which those with particular properties can be selected, will be developed with the aim of creating a new technology that can be applied to, e.g., the discovery of new antimicrobial compounds.
We have developed an autonomous system for programmed chemical synthesis based on synthetic molecular machinery constructed by DNA self-assembly. This system makes use of click ligation to create a record of reaction steps, a synthetic 'gene', which can be amplified (by cloning) and read back to identify reaction products. We have demonstrated the creation of small combinatorial libraries of oligomers and plan to develop the technology as a tool for molecular discovery, a key element of which is the autonomous, genetically programmed synthesis of combinatorial libraries of oligomers, with natural and unnatural backbones and side chains, from which function molecules (e.g. antimicrobial agents) can be selected. The importance of click ligation in this process is that it is effective in reaction conditions that would be incompatible with enzymatic ligation, allowing us to explore the full potential of synthetic, non-ribosomal systems for programmed synthesis of abiotic compounds. We have also explored the construction of DNA-based molecular motors as potential components in the next generations of molecular assembly lines.

2) The influenza virus is a member of a class of viruses that includes some of the most important human, animal and plant pathogens, such as rabies and Ebola virus. Understanding the mechanisms of the RNAP of the influenza virus is essential to further basic research into the virus, as well as aiding in the development of novel therapeutics against this potentially deadly infectious disease and stimulating work on other viruses belonging to this class of pathogens. Furthermore, through our studies we have developed novel single-molecule techniques and instrumentation that are applicable to the study of many biological processes involving protein-nucleic acid interactions.
Crystal structures of the in?uenza RNA polymerase (RNAP) have provided intriguing static snapshots of how the viral RNA genome is bound and copied. We have built upon our expertise in structural analysis of the influenza virus RNAP (Hengrung et al. Nature 527:114, 2015) and single-molecule studies of the interactions of the influenza virus RNAP with viral RNA (Tomescu, Robb et al. PNAS 111:E3335, 2014) to probe the RNA conformational rearrangements occurring during RNAP binding and replication. Using a highly sensitive, solution-based single-molecule FRET assay to measure distances between fluorophores located on the viral RNA promoter or RNAP, we showed that the polymerase-bound RNA exists in two conformations, corresponding to pre-initiation and initiation states (Robb et al. NAR 44(21):10304, 2016). This work allows us to propose a model of the dynamic processes that occur during early influenza virus RNA synthesis and provides novel insights into the replication mechanisms of the influenza virus RNA genome. 
In addition to our in vitro single molecule FRET work, we have also carried out in vivo experiments to study the interactions of the influenza virus and host cellular machineries. In particular, we have used multi-colour super-resolution imaging to investigate sites of viral transcription and replication in the host cell, thought to occur in distinct locations in the nucleus in close proximity to sites of cellular transcription/RNA processing. We have shown that viral ribonucleoprotein complexes form large 'super-clusters' within the nucleus; work is currently ongoing to further determine the exact nature of these large complexes.

3) CRISPR and the related technique of CRISPRi has revolutionized our ability to study genomes, genes and gene expression. A challenge when using the technology is linking many different nucleic acid binding regions to the core dCAS9 handle on the sgRNAs. CLICK chemistry offers a tractable solution to this problem and we have shows that CLICK chemistry is an effective way of producing sgRNAs. Using these constructs we have effectively knocked down transcription and examined the consequences. The impact of this work is to show how CLICK chemistry can be successfully applied to address pertinent biological problems in cells.
We have used CLICK chemistry to produce customised sgRNAs (linking multiple base pairing regions regions to the constant Cas9 handle region) for strand-specific repression of transcription in yeast. Tests show that the sgRNA produced using CLICK chemistry function identically to those produced from synthetic DNA. This offers an alternative method for producing sgRNA libraries for genome wide interrogation of transcription. 
We have studied transcription at selected loci using our CLICKED CRISPRi constructs. Our results show that contrary to the published literature, CRISPRi is not strand-specific. To do this we have examined the effect of CRISPRi at loci having well-characterised sense and antisense transcription. At HMS2 inhibition of antisense transcription using catalytically dead Cas9 also result in premature truncation of the overlapping sense transcript. Moreover, inhibiting the native antisense transcript leads to the production of an internally initiated shorter antisense transcript that also extends into the HMS2 sense promoter and represses expression. We show that CRISPRi functions best at genes subject to low levels of nascent transcription.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>With our collaborators in Southampton University, we are demonstrating and publishing a wide range of applications of click ligation, providing technical and scientific data and application examples to underpin the wider uptake and development of this new technology. Specific findings will form the basis of protected intellectual property, and may be developed through, e.g., licencing agreements through Oxford University Innovation and Southampton University's Research and Innovation Services.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>18E0133E-DC4B-408F-B0BF-A439721ABFDD</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5464ee75af7640.27966969</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Chemicals,Healthcare,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>8461255D-16CC-41EF-A549-B9591B2AF881</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Evolution of DNA-Templated Synthesis as a Tool for Materials Discovery.